[[Image:Makutra.jpg|thumb]] A '''makitra''' is a big clay [[bowl (vessel)|bowl]] with a rough surface. With the help of a special (usually wooden, rarely porcelain) "ball", makitra can be used for [[creaming (food)|creaming]] cake batter, [[egg (food)|eggs]] with [[sugar]], [[buttercream]], [[Quark (cheese)|quark]] for [[cheese cake]], and [[poppy seeds]] for [[kutia]]. It is perhaps most used in [[Eastern Europe]]an kitchens, for example in [[Poland]]<ref>{{Cite book | author = group work (coordinator: doc. dr Maria Szczygłowa), author of the chapter: mgr Krystyna Kopeć | title = Dobra kuchnia: żywienie w rodzinie | publisher = Wydawnictwo "Watra" | place = [[Warszawa]] | edition = V <!-- fifth --> | year = 1976 | pages = 47 | chapter = Dobra organizacja żywienia to oszczędność czasu, sił i pieniędzy | language=pl}}</ref> and [[Ukraine]].<ref>[http://www.wumag.kiev.ua/index2.php?param=pgs20054/134 Ukrainian Christmas eve dinner and suggestions how to cook some dishes for it], Welcome to Ukraine Magazine</ref>
A similar tool, called [[Suribachi and surikogi|suribashi]], is used in Japanese cuisine.
