{{Refimprove|date=September 2015}}
The '''Pareto priority index (PPI)''',<ref>{{cite web|last1=Munk|first1=Jared|title=The Six Sigma Approach to Project Selection|url=http://www.sixsigmadaily.com/the-six-sigma-approach-to-project-selection/|website=Six SIgma Daily|accessdate=4 September 2015|ref=1}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Gryna|first1=Frank M.|title=Quality planning and analysis : from product development through use|date=2001|publisher=McGraw-Hill|location=Boston, Mass. [u.a.]|isbn=978-0070393684|page=61|edition=4.}}</ref> so named because of its connection with the [[Pareto principle]], which is in turn named after the economist [[Vilfredo Pareto]], can be used to prioritize several (quality improvement) projects.  It is especially used in the surroundings of [[six sigma]] projects.  It has first been established by [[AT&T]].{{Citation needed|date=December 2008}}

The PPI is calculated as follows:

: <math> \text{PPI} = \frac{\text{savings} \times \text{probability of success}}{\text{cost} \times \text{time of completion}}</math>

A high PPI suggests a high project priority.

